# Regression for the final whole-branch review's Critical-1 finding: TWO
# sibling .gsx files in one package EACH caller-side-infer (no type args on
# the tag) against a shared generic component declared in a third sibling
# file. buildSkeleton used to construct a fresh inferRegistry per file, and
# inferRegistry.nextName counted "_gsxinfer1", "_gsxinfer2", ... PER
# REGISTRY, so a.gsx and b.gsx below would each hoist their own package-level
# `func _gsxinfer1[...]` — but every sibling file's skeleton is type-checked
# TOGETHER as one package, so the two identically-named funcs collided:
# `_gsxinfer1 redeclared in this block`, failing the WHOLE package even
# though neither file, considered alone, did anything wrong. The fix makes
# probe helper names unique PACKAGE-WIDE (one inferNameAllocator shared
# across every sibling file's buildSkeleton call), so this now generates
# cleanly. See generic_sibling_file.txtar for the single-inferring-file case
# this gap escaped from (that case infers in only ONE of the two files).
-- box.gsx --
package views

component Box[T string | int](value T) { <span>{value}</span> }
-- a.gsx --
package views

component A() { <Box value={1} /> }
-- b.gsx --
package views

component B() { <Box value={"hi"} /> }
-- invoke --
gsx.Fragment(A(), B())
-- diagnostics.golden --
-- render.golden --
<span>1</span><span>hi</span>
-- generated.x.go.golden --
